\b \cf0 What\'92s the difference between KUE and EKU?
\b0 \
The EKU is newer and tends to be considered \'93the\'94 usage-restriction mechanism, while KUE is usually considered less flexible. KUE is defined in terms of \'93operations\'94. EKU is defined in terms of \'93purpose\'94. EKU\'92s are usually checked offensively (i.e. \'93must have this EKU OID\'94), while KUE\'92s are usually checked defensively (i.e. \'93needs to have non-repudiation bit and may have encrypt/decrypt-only bit\'94). 
\f1 For a Certificate Authority, the list of purposes limits what kinds of certificates the authority can create; an operation must be included in both the authority and the certificates it signs to be valid.
